erica. Kai Erikson and Lori Peek expand our view of the disaster by assessing its ongoing impact on individual lives and across the wide-ranging geographies where displaced New Orleanians landed after the storm. Such an expanded view, the authors argue, is critical for understanding the human costs of catastrophe across time and space. Concluding with a broader examination of disasters in the years since Katrina—including COVID-19—The Continuing Storm is a sobering meditation on the duration of a catastrophe that continues to exact steep costs in human suffering.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aDisaster victimszUnited States. 0aDisastersxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005xSocial aspects. 0aNatural disastersxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aHurricane Katrina, New Orleans, disaster studies, natural disaster studies, hurricanes, sociology, Evacuation, how respond to environmental disasters, emergency management.1 aPeek, Lori, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076651640uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32433240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477324356423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477324356/original  a978-3-11-076651-6  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK